The paper deals with algorithms for computing simulation preorder and equivalence on Kripke structures, which are commonly used in formal verification and model checking. This topic is closely related to logic and automata theory, which are covered by the cs.LO (Logic in Computer Science) sub-category. Additionally, the paper involves partitioning the state space of Kripke structures, which is a problem in computational complexity and graph theory, falling under the cs.DS (Data Structures and Algorithms) sub-category. The use of simulation algorithms in model checking and verification also relates to artificial intelligence, which is covered by the cs.AI (Artificial Intelligence) sub-category. Finally, the paper involves analyzing the space and time complexity of the algorithm, which is a common theme in theoretical computer science and algorithms research, covered by the cs.PL (Programming Languages) and cs.LG (Machine Learning) sub-categories.
